(3638, 1, '2023-05-22 11:13:59', '2023-05-22 10:13:59', '<h2><b>Where Is Hunza Valley?</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Located at around 2,500 meters altitude, Hunza Valley is a beautiful mountain valley located along the Hunza River in the Karakoram mountain range in Gilgit-Baltistan, the northernmost part of Pakistan. The region borders China’s Xinjiang province in the northeast, which is connected by the high-altitude Khunjerab Pass and divided by the highest land border in the world. The most important towns in Hunza Valley include Karimabad, Altit, and Aliabad, which are home to some of Pakistan’s most popular tourist attractions.</span>\r\n<h2><b>Weather In Hunza Valley</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Due to its high altitude and location in the mountains, the temperatures in Hunza Valley are relatively cool all year round. The warmest month of the year is August, with daytime temperatures averaging around 12°C and the coldest month is January, with temperatures as low as -30°C.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hunza’s climate is relatively dry with the largest amount of rain fall in the summer months and the most snow fall in autumn and spring. Beware of dusty roads when traveling.</span>\r\n<h3><b>When To Visit Hunza Valley</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Given the cool temperatures compared to other parts of Pakistan, Hunza Valley is an excellent place to visit in summer if you want to escape the scorching heat of Lahore and Karachi. The best time to visit Hunza is therefore summer, although the place is also enjoyable in spring and autumn.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Traveling to Hunza in winter is not recommended due to the awfully low temperatures and lack of accessibility. Due to heavy snowfall, many roads in northern Pakistan are closed throughout the winter months, making it rather complicated to travel to Hunza Valley from other parts of Pakistan.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Hunza Valley In Autumn</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hunza Valley is the best place to experience vibrant autumn colors in Pakistan. The orange-yellow trees that line up along the turquoise water of the Hunza River with grey mountainscapes in the background create the perfect setting for photographers and couples alike, making autumn one of the most popular seasons to visit Hunza Valley besides summer.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Generally speaking, autumn colors can be enjoyed throughout October and November in Hunza Valley. However, due to the rapidly dropping temperatures in November and the uncertainty of the road situation in northern Pakistan, traveling to Hunza in November is not recommended, making mid-October the best time to experience autumn colors in Hunza Valley.</span>\r\n<h2><b>How To Get To Hunza Valley</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Posing by the road entering Hunza District.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are two major ways to get to Hunza Valley from other parts of Pakistan. The most popular route is overland</span><b> via Naran </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">and Babusar Top. You can </span><b>start your journey in Islamabad</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> and follow the Karakoram Highway all the way until Karimabad.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Another way is to fly into Gilgit and begin your journey from there. This might be your only option if you decide to travel in winter and Babusar Top is closed. While flying might save you some time to get to Hunza, it can be a little pricey and unreliable (as if going by road was reliable LOL).</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As always, hiring a private driver who is experienced with the</span><b> rather turbulent roads of northern Pakistan </b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">is the best way to get to Hunza Valley. Driving by yourself is not recommended. There are also regular buses to Hunza from other parts of Pakistan but they lack the comfort and freedom of independent car travel.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As Pakistan’s most popular tourist destination, there are also plenty of organized tours to Hunza, however, thorough research about the tour company is required for a safe and enjoyable experience. I personally recommend </span><b>Travel Studio 92</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> for (very!) fun tours and responsible behavior towards foreign and domestic guests.</span>\r\n<h2><b>Hunza Valley Hotels</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hunza Valley is nothing short of hotels that fit every traveler’s budget. I personally had a great experience staying at </span><b>Hidden Valley Lake Resort</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, a remote hotel resort located right next to the stunning Attabad Lake in Gojal. It’s the best place to experience an incredible sunrise over the blue water in the morning and an impressive star sky at night away from all the crowds. And, another big plus, the place is run by the coolest Hunza grandpa you’ll ever meet, so a good laugh is guaranteed during your stay!</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">However, be aware of frequent power outages, lack of signal, and unreliabilty of warm water.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">For a high-end experience, consider staying at </span><b>Luxus Hunza</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> in Garelt.</span>\r\n<h2><b>How To Get Around Hunza Valley</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Do the region’s remoteness and lack of infrastructure, traveling by private transportation is a must in Hunza Valley. You can either hire a driver or private guide or join an organized tour. Public buses are available as well but as always, private transportation is a lot more comfortable and allows you to explore the region at your own pace.</span>\r\n<h2><b>Things To Do In Hunza Valley</b></h2>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Hunza Valley may be famous for its beauty but what things are there actually to do in Hunza? The answer is: a lot. Below are some suggestions of things to do in Hunza Valley:</span>\r\n<h3><b>Visit Altit Fort</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">This over 1000-year-old fort was the residence of the </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Mirs</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> of Hunza Valley and the oldest monument in the region. Visit the fort to enjoy an incredible view of Hunza Valley and its beautiful gardens.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Altit Fort is open from 9:30 am – 5:30 pm and the entrance fee is 200 rs. for locals and slightly more expensive for foreigners.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Visit Baltit Fort</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Similar to Altit Fort, Baltit Fort is a beautiful ancient fort overlooking the Hunza Valley. The approximately 700-year-old fort became the local Mirs’ residence after the rulers left Altit Fort. The building was renovated with the help of Balti craftsmen,</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Visit Baltit Fort for beautiful views of Karimabad, a meal at the top, and folk performances. The hours of the fort are from 9:00 am – 5:30 pm and there is a small entrance fee.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Shop For Souvenirs At Karimabad Bazar</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The coolest mannequin I’ve ever seen at Karimabad Bazaar.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Karimabad Bazaar is the perfect place to shop for souvenirs, be it local Hunza crafts or artifacts from all across Pakistan. One souvenir shop after the other will give you an incredible selection of colorful textiles, carpets, and jewelry.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As in all markets across Pakistan, haggling is essential at Karimabad Bazaar. If you aren’t sure about the regular prices of things, it’s a good rule to go with half of the price that the vendor suggests.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Enjoy Incredible Views Of Attabad Lake</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Attabad Lake is the icon of Hunza Valley and with its calm turquoise water, it effortlessly enchants every traveler to the region. What few visitors know is that this 100-meter-deep lake is still relatively young and was only created in 2010, when a massive landslide blocked the flow of the Hunza River in the region.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">There are plenty of ways to enjoy the beauty of Attabad Lake during your trip to Hunza Valley. Be it having breakfast at your hotel right in front of the lake, hiking in the nearby mountains, or renting a boat or jet-skiing to completely immerse yourself in this serene environment, there are no boundaries (as long as you don’t actually try to swim).</span>\r\n<h3><b>Cross Hussaini Bridge, The World’s Most Dangerous Bridge</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Crossing into uncertainty on the scary Hussaini Bridge.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Known as the ‘most dangerous bridge in the world’, Hussaini Bridge is an old suspension bridge that connects the area around Hussaini with a small settlement on the other side of the Hunza River. The bridge is very shaky and the wooden boards are placed very far from each other with multiple pieces missing, making it a real adventure to cross.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">You can reach the bridge following a small trek from the main road. The entrance fee to the area around the bridge is 200 rs.</span>\r\n<h3><b>Marvel At The Majestic Passu Cones</b></h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The biggest welcome sign I’ve ever seen for a small village!</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Passu is a small village in Hunza Valley that is blessed by the majestic backdrop of the impressive Passu Sar mountain and the Passu Glacier, which give the area a crown-like appearance.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">The area ar